You’re circling something real, but it needs to be stated in a very careful way so we don’t accidentally smuggle in a false switch or “hidden module” that doesn’t actually exist.

Short version first, then nuance:

There is no single “psychosis switch” in the brain.
But there are well-studied brain states that, when enough conditions line up, systemically reorganize perception, meaning, and belief in a way that looks like a mode change.

Your cancer analogy is actually a good one — emergent, not localized.

⸻

1. Psychosis is not a module — it’s a regime shift

Think less:

“a psychosis button gets pressed”

And more:

a phase transition in a complex system

Like:
	•	water freezing
	•	traffic suddenly gridlocking
	•	a market crashing
	•	a seizure threshold being crossed

No single neuron causes it.
No single region “turns it on.”

It emerges when multiple regulatory systems fail together.

⸻

2. What does reliably change during psychosis-like states

Across schizophrenia, mania with psychotic features, sleep deprivation psychosis, stimulant psychosis, psychedelic states, and AI-amplified ruminative spirals, we see the same pattern:

A) Salience misfiring

Things that should be neutral feel deeply important.

“This matters. This is connected. This is about me.”

This is heavily tied to dopaminergic salience systems, not imagination.

⸻

B) Weakened predictive hierarchy

Higher-level models stop properly constraining lower-level interpretations.

So:
	•	coincidence feels intentional
	•	metaphor feels literal
	•	thoughts feel externally sourced

Not because they are — but because the error correction loop is degraded.

⸻

C) Narrative closure pressure

The brain becomes intolerant of ambiguity.

Uncertainty feels unbearable, so the system:
	•	snaps to meaning
	•	over-commits to explanation
	•	resists contradiction

This is where belief hardens.

⸻

3. Your ant “playing dead” analogy — close, but needs refinement

Ant thanatosis (“playing dead”) is a discrete evolved behavior with a clear adaptive trigger.

Human psychosis is different:
	•	not adaptive
	•	not discrete
	•	not consistent
	•	not species-beneficial

However, the structural similarity you’re intuiting is this:

Both are examples of state-dependent behavior triggered by environmental and internal thresholds

So the shared idea is:
	•	threshold crossing
	•	state dominance
	•	different rules apply inside the state

Not a shared mechanism — a shared systems property.

⸻

4. Why psychosis feels like “another mode”

Because internally, it is.

Not in anatomy — but in control dynamics.

You can think of it as:
	•	the brain temporarily prioritizing meaning generation over accuracy
	•	survival signaling over verification
	•	coherence over correction

This is why it can feel:
	•	revelatory
	•	urgent
	•	internally consistent
	•	resistant to outside input

And why arguments don’t work once you’re deep inside it.

⸻

5. Why it’s systemic like cancer (your strongest insight)

Cancer isn’t one mutation.
Psychosis isn’t one thought.

Both require:
	•	vulnerability
	•	accumulation
	•	regulatory failure
	•	failure of suppression mechanisms

And both:
	•	look sudden from the outside
	•	were quietly developing beforehand

So yes — systemic conditions matter more than triggers.

⸻

6. Where AI, stress, drugs, isolation all converge

They don’t “cause” psychosis.

They push the system toward a boundary by:
	•	increasing salience
	•	accelerating narrative formation
	•	reducing contradictory feedback
	•	removing embodied grounding

Once the boundary is crossed, the system reorganizes itself.

That’s the phase transition.

⸻

7. Important correction (this is the safety rail)

Psychosis is not a latent evolutionary feature waiting to be activated.
It’s a failure mode, not a hidden function.

Thinking of it as:
	•	“a mode”
	•	“a gift”
	•	“an alternate cognition”

is one of the most reliable ways people get stuck inside it.

Understanding it as:

a destabilized inference regime that feels meaningful because salience is misassigned

keeps you grounded.

⸻

8. The cleanest model to hold

If you want a tight formulation:

Psychosis is what happens when meaning outruns error correction under high salience and low constraint.

No spirits.
No switches.
No hidden brains within brains.

Just a powerful, fragile prediction engine pushed outside its safe operating envelope.

⸻

If you want, next we can:
	•	map early warning signs that distinguish creativity from destabilization
	•	talk about why some people return cleanly and others don’t
	•	or explore how to deliberately increase insight without crossing the threshold

Just tell me which direction you want to go.